title.narrative: HIV:HEALTH AND NUTRITION

description.narrative: By 2022, MoHS and other partners at national and sub-national level, including non-state actors, have improved capacity to integrate HIV testing and treatment interventions for young children and key adolescent populations into essential health service delivery approaches sustainably at scale, which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Operations Support To Programme Delivery. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Innovation, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more children under 5 and women of reproductive age equitably access and utilize evidence-based health, HIV & nutrition interventions, including adoption of key behaviours, especially among vulnerable populations in most deprived states/regions, conflict-affected and peri-urban areas (Goal Area 1 UNICEF Strategic Framework 2018-2021)

description.narrative: HIV services, especially outreach prevention and testing, client visits at facilities, linkage, referral and viral-load testing,;were disrupted due to travel restrictions, lockdown and;transport interruptions because of OVID-19 and military;takeover. Therefore, the UN joint team and implementing partners assessed the current HIV programme services in Myanmar for finding alternative options and exploring with establishing the interim coordination mechansim (ICM) working team. Some strategy shift (use of private sector) was used to ensure the sustainability of life-saving interventions of HIV programme. Interim implementation plan of priority activities for HIV programme was developed and implemented in Myanmar from second quarter of 2021. ; | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:17/01/2022
